hey, i'm not sure i've got my USB2.0 connectors right on my mobo. there's 4 connectors per USB slot, but there's 9 pins on the mobo (which allows connecting 2 USB ports) the really weird thing here... there are 2 of these 9 pin-ers. 1 is USB 2.0, the other is USB 1.1. Everything worked fine when I had the 2.0 wired up to the rear USB ports, and the 1.1 to the front. I simply swapped them, and now the back ports are at 1.1, and the front ports 2.0 is not functioning properly when the ASUS provided USB2.0 drivers are installed, slipping a USB Flash Drive in has no effect whatsoever when I let windows install it's own driver, it detects the insertion, but says the device is unrecognized, and possibly malfunctioning... i'm flumoxxed any ideas? when windows installs it's own drivers, it doesn't prompt for a restart... could that be it? i should try it prolly what OS do you use? (which distro?) i tried that last summer. the compilation process took something like 6 hours, and then it hit some glitch and failed. kismet_: the pin that doesn't have a neighbour is no connection, used simply as a key usually, the pins next to that one are ground, then d+ then d- then +5v but different boards can have different pinouts. your board's pinout should be in its manual maybe the cables to your front ports are picking up too much noise for usb2 to transfer data without errors move them as far away from sources of noise (like your graphics card and power cables) and see how you go you could also see if wrapping them in grounded alfoil helps i haven't used windows in years gentoo exclusively kismet_: it has a few quirks, but I find they're well worth the control that only gentoo gives me over my systems xen is a virtualisation patch for the linux kernel oh that.. they're using many of the ideas from it in xorg i hear simply offloading more and more of the graphics processing to the video card Xgl does all drawing operations via opengl, which means the video card driver decides what's done by the card and what's done by the cpu then shipped to the card still needs a lot of work I hear

Anne, [new topic] :-) Does XHR attempt to define how to handle non-ASCII characters in the URL? we might, but then it was so long ago I don't recall the algorithm it refers to doesn't seem to deal with IRI vs URI well, the question is what is being put on the wire. if you have non-ASCII characters in the IRI, what do you do with them? see, the question is whether it's the same if we only have IE doing the wrong thing I'm happy wait if we can rely on http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3987#section-3.1 than it's probably fine, but mentioning it wouldn't hurt I just tested [] with XHR in Opera, and it get's unescaped on the wire (in the path) I have no problem with that, unless someone pretends that there already is a certain behavior that is needed for web compatibility when that is not the case I agree that not escaping [] will be harmless in practice the question is how specific IRIbis need to get in descibing the behavior for broken IRIs that's what I'm trying to find out well, there is no uniform behavior right now I have no problem documenting what various impls do, but I don't see a reason why that would be more than an implementation report; but sure, we had *that* discussion sufficiently often

it defers to parse a URL didn't we discuss this already? does it have to? dunno, what happens for <a>? how is it different? anyway, all browsers other than IE handle IRIs fine is your issue that it is not clear that IRIs need to be converted to URIs before being used in HTTP? is not that not stated in the IRI spec? we had this exact discussion on the mailing list some time ago http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/public-webapi/2008Jun/0092.html goes back to CSS good to know you're more supportive of it now though sure i think what hixie tried to do with html5 url parsing was to make browsers "conforming" cause [] in path is clearly not a valid URI and servers could reject it (though most don't, so presumably they do not use compliant URL parsers either) or URI parsers or whatever only if your goal is to not specify details and let implementors reverse engineer each other for a bit it's been shown time and again that doing the same is far more useful than just differing a bit for the sake of exactly nothing documenting what impls do is not interesting at all imo

Steve: page-break-before, page-break-after, and named pages Howcome: I would be so confused by having different behavior for page-break-before and page-break-after Steve: I am convinced that we should preserve margin on page-break-before Steve: but not page-break-after 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d agrees with 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4 Murakami-san: I agree with 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4. Page-break-before and page-break-after should behave the same. Steve: I want a use case for page-break-after 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: Suppose I want to print CSS2.1 with breaks between sections and chapters 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: I want page-break-before on each chapter, to separate out the chapters from each other and from the cover pages 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: but I select page-break-after for the sections, because the beginning of the chapter is usually so short, just a title and maybe a paragraph or two discussion of use cases and margins and breaking Steve: Ok, I can live with it Anne: It's really annoying for projection mode that the margin is collapsed at breaks RESOLVED: margins kept at forced breaks for page-break-before and page-break-after what about named pages? if we collapse there, you always have the option of forcing the break to keep the margin and you're not guaranteed a break, because elements assigned to the same name do not break in betweenm one of the main use cases for named pages is e.g. putting a wide table onto a landscape page RESOLVED: If a page-break-before, page-break-after, or use of named page forces a page break, then the margin top is preserved after the break. Discussion of use cases for preserving margins at unforced breaks there definitely seem to be some, e.g. for headings Murakami-san proposes margin-before-conditionality: auto | discard | retain 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4 mentions that registration (preserving line alignment) might solve some of these problems general agreement that this problem exists and we should solve it, but not for 3.0 margin-before-conditionality.. 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4 objects to 'before' suggestion margin-conditionality, can be treated as shorthand later if we need separate controls Steve: 'conditionality' is hard to spell Howcome: 'keep' instead of 'retain'? seem to have agreement on that discard seems to be ok Other names: margin-collapse, margin-break Looking at margin-break: auto | discard | keep Murakami-san: what about the margin-after? 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d draws margin-break: [ auto | discard | keep ] keep? (well, first draws margin-break: [ auto | discard | keep]{1,2} but refines to above since margin is always discarded at bottom by default ) Second value applies to margin-after. Defaults to discarding margin if not specified. Murakami-san notes that this control also applies to the first margin in the document. ACTION 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4 add to GCPM draft as a holding place until next Paged Media draft is started LUNCH BREAK margin-break: auto | discard | keep | keep-all ?

It's meant to work even if the author provides no JS. Are there minimal UI requirements in the spec here? is looking Not even "you have to tell the user and not just silently fail"? That seems like a pretty reasonable UI requirement to me. I'm talking about browsers here.  Googlebot is not a browser. A Googlebot does not fall into the "Web browsers and other interactive user agents" category. It's "Data mining tools", I suppose. So it only has to follow the semantic requirements, not UI requirements. http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/multipage/association-of-controls-and-forms.html#constraint-validation "Report the problems with the constraints of at least one of the elements given in unhandled invalid controls to the user." edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: I think the heading information for your table is almost right now The finalk thing is that the <th>Day 2</th> has "Day 1" as one of its headings (and so on down the page) This is because these headers aren't assigned any heading information from the scope algorithm and HTML 4 says "In the absence of header information from either the scope or headers attribute, user agents may construct header information according to the following algorithm" From the implicit algorithm. I think it's an incorrect reading of the HTML 4 spec, but I don't know what the right reading is. Because, at the moment, my implementation assumes that ""In the absence of header information from either the scope or headers attribute" applies to the cell we are trying to assign a heading to in the case of the <th> cell containing "Day 2" there is no information from any scope or headers attribute that assigns heading information to that cell edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: But does HTML 4 actually say that? My reading is that if a cell has no heading information supplied from headers or scope you then do the row/column search ignoring scope or headers attributes edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: agreed My imp. of the HTML 5 algorithm seems to get that right My conclusion from playing with a few tables on the net is that nothing always makes sense cc097e0d7183ae8436e7df709553c8c0: I'm interested insofar as it it necessary to show people that vauge = bad + probably illogical (illogical in non-trivial cases, that is)

A good example would be demographics. say you have area then pop in the thead then you have each rowgroup as a continent with total pop then you have countries in each rowgroup row with their respective pop Don't forget that a td can be a header simultaneously with being a data cell. edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: yes it is. it's stated in the DTD is there anything that contradicts that? edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: I think trying to read the comments against the prose doesn't make much sense. Specifications aren't meant to be read to be self-contradicting. :) (They might be self-contradicting by accident, but you don't seem to be arguing that's the case here.) edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: Actually the prose does say: "Note that it's not always possible to make a clean division of cells into headers or data. You should use the TD element for such cells together with the id or scope attributes as appropriate." Which seems a relatively clear restatement of the principle. edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: Yes. But they are all intended to help explain the spec, not contradict it. therefore trying to read them as a source of contradictions, like two alternative sources for the same thing, is strange (that quote is from 11.4.1) edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: also note the example intended to illustrate the scope attribute which features td with the scope="row" followed by the text in the prose: "Although the first cell in each row contains data, not header information, the scope attribute makes the data cell behave like a row header cell." edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: Actually looking through the prose throughout supports that comment. I can't see how one could construct anything contradicting the comment. cc097e0d7183ae8436e7df709553c8c0: Depends on whether "figuring out an algorithm ... that works with existing tables" without consulting the spec that data table creators used is a realistic task. I suspect it isn't. I think that's a very important part of the process too. edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: What I am saying is it's unrealistic to /only/ do that. (because the spec is a guide to well-authored tables that aren't sampled and unlearning resources are a guide to badly authored ones)

CRXLPY: As opposed to the risk that someone might glance at their un-colorized logs and think it was someone else talking to them, rather than them talking to someone else. It also makes copy-and-pasted lines more easily understandable. For example... <CRXLPY> I hilight As opposed to... (Konversation is almost a KDE clone of X-Chat but, unlike X-Chat, it has irssi's "sort by how recently they talked" feature for tab completion)

Hixie: Chicken Hixie: Chicken/egg problem, though isn't FF 3.5 supposed to have improved support for such microformats? What's a real shame is that Google doesn't cull information from our business listings that are all in microformats. c74f596e4fe95fc3bb8726dbde2031b0: I think the issue is that web surfers that browse to the site aren't able to make use of the microformats due to not having any built in ability in the browser. You could write a plugin, but you're still excluding the vast majority of people that wouldn't be able to figure it out. In this case, just exporting an iCal file would be easier. That type of support should be built into IE. But you already said that support for it would be simple. A rather large percentage of the Internet has contact information and events built into web pages.  If those were all built as microformats, it'd make sense to build support in for the browser. It'd be like not including SVG support. Ideally browsers would support all official web standards out of box, and microformats would gain some sort of official status. HTML 4.01 is an official standard. One would hope it is supported by the browser. Are you suggesting JavaScript be moved to a plugin? Fine, then include all of those plugins by default, including ones that support microformats. If most users have browsers that support microformats, then that would solve the issue. Oh wait, I think I see what might be being said. Yeah, I see that now. But I fail to see the point. Reading the microformat and getting an iCal file would be functionally identical, and that is the purpose.  If they want to "interact" with the event then they just need to add a form and maybe publish an API if someone wants to write an application for it. Ala, writing a Facebook application. I guess someone could suggest adding a tag to indicate that the Microformat fields are empty and are meant to be filled in by the client. Like creating a form with everything tagged as an hCal, and at the root have class="userSubmit" or something. Then an application could automatically find a form and fill data in to the proper fields automatically. But I'm still not seeing how that would be useful in any practical sense. Someone would need to specify then that form elements MUST not be scrubbed for data. That could be problematic. I suppose you could have a plugin that lets you fill in contact or calender information always using the exact same looking interface, and then that filled in form. What if someone assigns a value to one of those form fields?  How do you make sure a microformat plugin doesn't think that is a contact? It would actually be nice to be able to automatically fill in all contact fields in a form. slaps forehead. You're right. I think we still come back to the issue of "What's the point?" And that is the only use I can think of. That doesn't even apply to a calender. It seems like a lot of work to go through too for a minute or two of saved time every so often. Yeah, standard field names are nice. Anything but this though.  http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc3106 Ecom_ShipTo_Telecom_Phone_Number? Seriously?

Hixie: if someone wants a parser to do something, build one. The reason adding to calendar (/subscribing in google calendar) is the big one is because it's what everyone wanted to build building a microformats parser is pretty simple if you have a decent HTML parser available, which many languages do b5ef00f170716a058ad31a979fb22efd: NEVER build that kind of cruft into a browser. That's what extensions/userscripts/plugins/other things are for So include a link to export said iCal data from the microformats, or also output iCal (it's not hard) I heartily disagree Browsers have too much crap in them as it is I said building a parser to do something is simple... that doesn't mean it belongs native in the browser The complaint was about behaviours if you build it into the browser, it's still only going to be able to be added to a calendar unless you build another behaviour and if you build another behaviour, just do it with existing tools I like the idea of SVG support being a plugin, actually, but that's a seperate matter The point is that the original complaint was that there was only one obvious action Where that action lives makes no difference Ideally browsers would only be content rendering windows to hang plugin on, and there would be no such thing as "official status" but we're never going to get there, so we work with what we have :) It's a W3C standard, and thus official for those who recognise their authority One would hope that most user agents would process HTML by default, yes, but it need not be a feature of all of them, there's no rule about that b5ef00f170716a058ad31a979fb22efd: I'm suggesting *everything* be moved to a plugin Modular designs rule But I've already conceeded that people are too rooted in their ways to do that b5ef00f170716a058ad31a979fb22efd: sure, but that still doesn't solve the root problem Hixie brought up The issue was that "supporting microformats" only means "let them add to a calendar"... ie, not enough actions/behaviours available As do I... adding to calendar seems to be all people care about (as evidenced by it being all they've built)...  I've been working on a good "invite others" action as well (bookmarklet), not done yet b5ef00f170716a058ad31a979fb22efd: microformats are kind of for data... not forms empty ones are not so useful better idea: use the class names from microformat be used as the name= attribute on the form (I tend to do this anyway) more semantic, and acheives the same goal http://pastie.org/467373 b5ef00f170716a058ad31a979fb22efd: a microformat plugin won't see it, because the class names aren't set to anything microformatty (or anything at all in this case) Quite possibly Although: 03:59 < b5ef00f170716a058ad31a979fb22efd> It would actually be nice to be able to automatically fill in all contact fields in a form. True. 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: i can't get to that site, is it down? it's the same style="" rathole we've always had 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c_: <font> and style="" are "low quality" because they are media-specific, and potentially hide information from non-presentational UAs. 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c_: <div>s-containing-inlines are "low quality" because they imply some sort of paragraphing structure without giving any information about why 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c_: (typically, the latter is used as a workaround for the lack of a widget abstraction language like xbl) ok, strike the media-specific part (though i actually do believe they usually result in media-specific content, even if it's technically possible to use them otherwise) i considered including <style>, but in practice if you use a style sheet with selectors you tend to be pushed towards content that can stand even without the stylesheet. obviously though that's not automatically the case, which is why the other mode wouldn't be called "high quality" indeed oh come now oh i don't know that it could be quantified but it certainly is clear to me that you can improve the quality of almost any document with <font>, style="", or <div>s-containing-inlines, whereas i don't think the same can be said of all documents that do not have those characteristics. objectively? i don't know i haven't looked at it in detail it's not really a proposal just an idea i don't think we can drop style="", <font>, and <div>s-containing-inlines altogether but i do think that we should discourage their use in favour of the alternatives ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: it's not really compatibility either, since if we were desigining the language from scratch, you'd still want these features 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c: i'm not even talking about legacy content, even for a brand new language with no content i think these features are necessary, e.g. for prototyping nor am i talking about abuse you can abuse <ins> and <del> and anything else i'm talking about completely conforming and correct uses i agree it's a case-by-case problem sometimes style="" has to be replaced with samething else, e.g. using a different element altogether granted, but it seems better than giving the impression that a page that uses only <div>s and style="" is fine. bbl yeah how? there are pages that consist of nothing but <div>s and style=""s or even just <div>s and stylesheets it might not affect _those_ pages, but i think it would help with people the same way that having "strict" vs "transitional" has helped some in terms of mindshare growth

69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I don't see how style="" is media-specific 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: it lacks the ability to give different styles per media, but can still be used in media-independent ways since in practice most styles are not media-scoped anyway, nor do they need to be in that case, style="" hides no more information than <style>, <link rel="stylesheet"> or <style scoped> none of which you have labelled "low quality" I have to go grab a beer, brb back if you include <style> and <link rel="stylesheet"> it would make it pretty hard to have a useful non-low-quality document but I don't think there's any evidence of a difference in hiding information from non-presentational UAs between those and style="" I mean, that might be the case, but I am not sure how you would quantify it is there any way to show evidence for or against? obviously it's hard to argue against your proposal if it is based on an an unfalsifiable claim ok, s/proposal/idea/ dropping all those would certainly make a lot of documents nonconforming for seemingly-gratuitous reasons I just don't see any reason to discourage style="" if <style scoped> won't be similarly discouraged the latter can be abused in all the same ways, the main difference is that it is more verbose and less compatible with compatible with existing UAs ok, let me put it this way I don't think systematically replacing all style="" with <style scoped> would improve any documents thus, creating an incentive to do so (badge-seeking behavior, etc) seems like a bad idea I agree such documents are not great; just not sure how to make a good machine-checkable rule that detects bad style

Could call it "Compatibility" instead of "Low quality", and have it provide the features that are compatible with implementations and content and forbid things that are likely to cause authors pain and not attempt to make subjective judgements of value That seems to resulted in people choosing to use transitional twenty times more often than strict

69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: i think having different conformance levels is a bad idea. we should just allow style="" and <div>s containing inlines but perhaps discourage the former for authors by saying that they are conforming, and then having a note about why style="" can be harmful this way, badge hunters won't replace their style=""s with more verbose but no better alternatives, and people can cite the spec about why people shouldn't use style="" (i don't think <div>s containing inlines is harmful) indeed they are not going to disappear if we label them non-conforming, but some might be rewritten to use constructs that pass validation without increasing the quality or semantics i don't think labeling them non-conforming will result in them being rewritten to use semantic markup hmm, perhaps

1f8387eb43f131d7c309a90a4e36b5cb: I'd be cautious in calling any geometry conventions a "standard" :-) People can't even decide which handedness to use for axes, or which way around to write matrices That orientation spec says "Positive rotation around an axis is defined as clockwise when viewed along the positive direction of the axis." a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: The spec says C is perpendicular to the screen and outwards, so if the screen is lying flat on its back then C is vertically upwards so you have to look along the upwards direction i.e. from beneath and then rotate clockwise (for positive angles) which is equivalent to anticlockwise when you're looking down on it (and you start with the screen lying flat on its back with the top pointing North) (and rotate around C first) (so that's the right way to turn it to make its top point West) prefers it with sub-pixel rendering enabled on Linux on a cheap laptop display and on a better LCD It's subtle enough that I don't notice the colours, and its makes vertical lines a tiny bit thicker so they better match the non-axis-aligned lines, I think s/its/it/
